title: Friedrich Nietzsche - Philosophical Works, Part II (11 books)
description:
This is an update to my earlier collection of 28 works by Friedrich Nietzsche in English translation which can be accessed here:
 <a href="
http://thepiratebay.se/torrent/9386147/" rel="nofollow" target="_NEW">
http://thepiratebay.se/torrent/9386147/</a>

Eleven new titles are added in this collection, the most important of which are all 5 volumes published to date in the new critical translation of The Complete Works of Nietzsche being published by Stanford University Press (1995- ).


They are all in PDF format:

* DAWN: Thoughts on the Presumptions of Morality - Volume 5 of the Collected Works (Stanford University Press,  2011).  Translated by Brittain Smith.

* THE DIONYSIAN VISION OF THE WORLD (Univocal, 2013).  Translated by Ira J. Allen.

* HUMAN, ALL TOO HUMAN I: A Book For Free Spirits (University of Nebraska Press, 1996).  Translated by Marion Faber, with Stephen Lehmann.

* HUMAN, ALL TOO HUMAN I: A Book For Free Spirits - Volume 3 of the Collected Works (Stanford University Press,  1997).  Translated by Gary Handwerk.

* HUMAN, ALL TOO HUMAN II and Unpublished Fragments from the Period of Human, All Too Human II (Spring 1878 - Fall 1879) - Volume 4 of the Collected Works (Stanford University Press,  2012).  Translated by Gary Handwerk.

* ON TRUTH AND UNTRUTH: Selected Writings (HarperCollins, 2010).  Translated and edited by Taylor Carman.

* PHILOSOPHY AND TRUTH: Selections from Nietzsche's Notebooks from the Early 1870s (Humanities, 1979).   Edited and translated by Daniel Breazeale.

* THE PRE-PLATONIC PHILOSOPHERS (University of Illinois Press, 2001).  Translated and edited by Greg Whitlock.

* UNFASHIONABLE OBSERVATIONS - Volume 2 of the Collected Works (Stanford University Press,  1995).  Translated by Richard T. Gray.

* UNPUBLISHED WRITINGS FROM THE PERIOD OF UNFASHIONABLE OBSERVATIONS - Volume 11 of the Collected Works (Stanford University Press,  1999).  Translated by Richard T. Gray.

* WRITINGS FROM THE EARLY NOTEBOOKS (Cambridge University Press, 2009).  Translated by Raymond Geuss and Alexander Nehamas.
